properties.occurrenceRemarks: Same spider but I did get an underside pic so hoping for a more precise ID
properties.identificationRemarks: Southern based on two factors. Lateral lines on mactans are usually white red, with variolus being usually white. The first read spot/line is wider than the second usually on mactans and the second is usually wider than the first on variolus. Edit: I would like to ad that from the shot, it does appear that the hourglass is likely wider on the anterior side and it doesn't look like it is broken, but I wouldn't want to use it for ID without a more direct shot. Males are harmless, but I wouldn't want to disturb the guy.

properties.occurrenceRemarks: Same spider but I did get an underside pic so hoping for a more precise ID
properties.identificationRemarks: Southern based on two factors. Lateral lines on mactans are usually white red, with variolus being usually white. The first read spot/line is wider than the second usually on mactans and the second is usually wider than the first on variolus. Edit: I would like to ad that from the shot, it does appear that the hourglass is likely wider on the anterior side and it doesn't look like it is broken, but I wouldn't want to use it for ID without a more direct shot. Males are harmless, but I wouldn't want to disturb the guy.

properties.occurrenceRemarks: The spider has a predominately shiny black appearance with a reddish-orange hour glass figure on the underside of its abdomen. The spider itself is about a half an inch long with the thickness of its abdomen coming out to around 10 mm. It’s web was tucked away and hidden in the corner of an electrical box with a very sporadic web shape consistency. Based on the body features of this spider it looks to be a female black widow.
